      <body>
         <div type="edition"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:lang="grc"
              subtype="transcription"
              xml:id="zoor0107.transcription"
              corresp="#zoor0107.translation">
            <p>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Μνημῖον</sic>
                  <corr>Μνημεῖον</corr>
               </choice>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Σύβελλα</sic>
                  <corr>Σιβύλλης</corr>
               </choice>
               <lb/> Ἀρρενίου, <choice>
                  <sic>παυσόμενη</sic>
                  <corr>παυσάμενη</corr>
               </choice>
               <lb/> μετὰ καλοῦ <choice>
                  <sic>ἀνόμα<lb/>τος</sic>
                  <corr>ὀνόματος</corr>
               </choice>
                    καὶ καλῆς πίστε<lb/>ως ἐτῶν κθʹ,<lb/> ἔτους τιʹ,<lb/>
               <expan><abbr>μη</abbr><ex>νὸς</ex></expan> Ἀρτεμισίου ηιʹ,<lb/>
               <choice><abbr>ἡμρ</abbr><ex>ἡμέρᾳ</ex></choice>
               <expan><abbr>Κυ</abbr><ex>ρίου</ex></expan> ζʹ.<lb/>
               <choice>
                  <sic>Θάρσι</sic>
                  <corr>Θάρσει</corr>
               </choice>, <choice>
                  <sic>Σύβελλα</sic>
                  <corr>Σίβυλλα</corr>
               </choice>, <choice>
                  <sic>ου<lb/>δὶς</sic>
                  <corr>ουδείς</corr>
               </choice> ἀθάνατος.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation"
              ana="#b1"
              xml:id="zoor0107.translation"
              corresp="#zoor0107.transcription">
            <p>Monument of Sybella (Sibylla), (daughter) of Arrenios, who died having a good
                    name and good faith (at the age) of 29 years, in (the) year 310, on (the) 18th
                    (day) of the month Artemisios, on the 7th day of (the) Lord (Saturday). Be of
                    good cheer, Sybella, no one (is) immortal.</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription provides the date as the 7th day of the Lord (Saturday), the 18th day of the month Artemisios in the year 310 according to the Era of the Province of Arabia, that is, May 8, 415 CE. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in Byzantine Zoora. The majority of the Greek tombstones from this location have been identified as Christian. The rectangular tombstone is broken in the upper right corner and chipped in the lower half. Its smoothed, inscribed surface is flaked off in several places, especially in the lower section. The text, written in predominantly round script except for a few square omicrons and sigmas, is engraved and preserves traces of red and yellow paint in lines one through six. The text is set within incised, single or double guide-lines, which extend two lines beyond the end of the text. An outlined sun-disc drawn in heavy red paint is centered above the text. A decorative motif consisting of interlaced vertical snakes drawn in red paint appears to the right of the text. In line six, the year numeral is flanked by a pair of angular motifs drawn in red paint. The text contains both spelling and grammatical errors. This occurrence of the prophetic name Σίβυλλα is otherwise unattested in Palestine and Arabia. The name Ἀρρένιος, probably a Greek rendering of the Latin gentilicum Arrenius, is otherwise unknown in Palestine.</p>
         </div>
